      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): honor explicit accountId token resolution in cron deliveries",
        "body": "## Summary\n- prevents explicit non-default Discord `accountId` sends from silently inheriting the default/top-level token\n- returns `source: none` when the explicit account has no token instead of falling back to default identity\n- adds regression coverage in `extensions/discord/src/token.test.ts`\n\n## Problem\nIn multi-account Discord setups, cron delivery can carry an explicit `accountId`, but token resolution currently falls back to default/top-level token when that explicit account token is absent/unresolved. That can make deliveries appear from the wrong bot identity and makes account-routing failures hard to detect.\n\n## Fix\nIn `resolveDiscordToken(...)`:\n- treat explicit non-default `accountId` as strict resolution scope\n- if no account token resolves for that explicit account, return `{ token: \"\", source: \"none\" }`\n- do not fall back to default/top-level token in that path\n\n## Tests\n- updated expectation: explicit non-default account without token does not inherit top-level token\n- added test: unknown explicit non-default account does not inherit default/top-level token\n- ran:\n  - `~/scripts/sandbox-heavy.sh pnpm test -- extensions/discord/src/token.test.ts`\n\n## Prior art\nThis follows the same safety principle as Telegram account token resolution hardening in [#5055](https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/5055): explicit account targeting should not silently resolve through a different account path.\n\nMade with [Cursor](https://cursor.com)",
        "branch": "fix/discord-cron-account-token-resolution",
